<subSubSection pageId="102" pageNumber="103" type="preliminary conservation status">
<paragraph pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Preliminary conservation status</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="102" pageNumber="103">
(
<bibRefCitation author="IUCN" journalOrPublisher="Annales de Biologie" pageId="109" pageNumber="110" publicationUrl="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" refId="B56" refString="IUCN, 2014. Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 11., http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" title="Guidelines for Using the IUCN Red List Categories and Criteria. Version 11" url="http://www.iucnredlist.org/documents/RedListGuidelines.pdf" year="2014">IUCN 2014</bibRefCitation>
). Vulnerable (VU B1a, biii). EOO 19,845 km2 (VU), AOO 56 km2 (EN). Although 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum truncicola" order="Solanales" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="truncicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Solanum truncicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been been consistently but sparsely recorded over a coherent stretch of the eastern Malagasy rainforest from Toamasina in the northernmost part of its distribution range to the Ambalavao area in the southernmost part, the highly fragmented nature of these eastern forest habitats gives cause for conservation concern.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="104" lastPageNumber="105" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="103" lastPageNumber="104" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum truncicola" order="Solanales" pageId="102" pageNumber="103" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="truncicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="102" pageNumber="103">Solanum truncicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a rare and unusual montane forest shrub or epiphyte. It is easily identifiable by its coriaceous leaves and long, almost linear calyx 
<pageBreakToken pageId="103" pageNumber="104" start="start">lobes</pageBreakToken>
which are divided to the base before the corolla begins to expand (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 30" captionStartId="F30" captionText="Figure 30. Solanum truncicola Bitter. A Flowering branch B Open flower C Fruiting branch D Stem showing minute simple pubescence E Simple trichome F Mature (?) berry. (Based on: A Malcomber et al. 1353; B Philipson et al. 5875 drawn from photographs; C-F Randrianasolo et al. 1163). Scale bar: A, C = 3 cm; B = 1.5 cm; D, F = 7 mm; E = 0.3 mm. Drawn by Lucy T. Smith." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.66.8457.figure30" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/95603" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">30A</figureCitation>
). The length of the calyx lobes (0.4-1.1 cm) in combination with the deeply stellate corollas with narrow lobes makes its flowers appear to be two overlapping stars (see Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. Flowers of species in the ANS clade. A Solanum africanum Mill. (South Africa, Rebelo s. n. - no herbarium voucher) B Solanum imamense Dunal (Madagascar, Rakotavao 5128) C Solanum madagascariense Dunal (Madagascar, Vorontsova et al. 498) D Solanum sambiranense D'Arcy &amp; Rakot. (Madagascar, Randrianasolo 580) E Solanum terminale Forssk. (Kenya, Vorontsova et al. 93) F Solanum truncicola Bitter (Madagascar, Antilahimena et al. 7846). Photo credits: A Tony Rebelo; B Charles Rakotavao; C, E Maria Vorontsova; D Richard Randrianasolo; E Patrice Antilahimena." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.66.8457.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/95573" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">1F</figureCitation>
). Petioles of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum truncicola" order="Solanales" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="truncicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Solanum truncicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the shortest of all Madagascar 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum" order="Solanales" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Solanum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (1-5 mm), usually less than 1/8 of the total leaf length. The flowers can reach 3 cm in diameter, and anthers to 6 mm in length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="104" lastPageNumber="105" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">
Misidentification of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum truncicola" order="Solanales" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="truncicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Solanum truncicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not likely, even though its height, internode length, and leaf size vary spectacularly across its distribution range: leaves of the type specimen are ca. 1.5 cm long, while leaves on other collections reach 13 cm. Some large leaved forms become reminiscent of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum myrsinoides" order="Solanales" pageId="103" pageNumber="104" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="myrsinoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="103" pageNumber="104">Solanum myrsinoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in habit and can be distin 
<pageBreakToken pageId="104" pageNumber="105" start="start">guished</pageBreakToken>
from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum myrsinoides" order="Solanales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="myrsinoides">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Solanum myrsinoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by their inflorescences of 1-2 (versus 2-6) flowers and calyx lobes 0.4-1.1 cm (versus less than 0.1 cm) long.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="104" pageNumber="105">
<bibRefCitation author="Bitter, G" journalOrPublisher="Botanische Jahrbuecher fuer Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="416 - 506" refId="B5" refString="Bitter, G, 1917. Solana Africana II. Botanische Jahrbuecher fuer Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie 54: 416 - 506" title="Solana Africana II." volume="54" year="1917">Bitter (1917)</bibRefCitation>
correctly described 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum truncicola" order="Solanales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="truncicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Solanum truncicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as distinct from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum humblotii" order="Solanales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humblotii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Solanum humblotii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum truncicola" order="Solanales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="truncicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Solanum truncicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum humblotii" order="Solanales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humblotii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Solanum humblotii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by its petioles 0.1-0.5 cm (versus 0.6-1 cm) long, acute (versus acuminate) leaves, glabrous (versus pubescent) young stems, narrowly ovate to obovate (versus deltate to acuminate) calyx lobes, and a different overall appearance. 
<bibRefCitation author="D'Arcy, WG" journalOrPublisher="Museum National D'Histoire Naturelle, Paris" pageId="107" pageNumber="108" pagination="1 - 146" refId="B25" refString="D'Arcy, WG, Rakotozafy, A, 1994. Flore de Madagascar et des Comores. Museum National D'Histoire Naturelle, Paris: 1 - 146" title="Flore de Madagascar et des Comores" year="1994">
<normalizedToken originalValue="D’Arcy">D'Arcy</normalizedToken>
and Rakotozafy (1994)
</bibRefCitation>
included 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum truncicola" order="Solanales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="truncicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Solanum truncicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a synonym of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum humblotii" order="Solanales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humblotii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Solanum humblotii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, perhaps because 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bitter’s">Bitter's</normalizedToken>
key only highlighted the more superficial indumentum and size differences between the two species, and the type collections were not carefully consulted. During the years that followed 
<normalizedToken originalValue="D’Arcy">D'Arcy</normalizedToken>
and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Rakotozafy’s">Rakotozafy's</normalizedToken>
treatment, many specimens of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum truncicola" order="Solanales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="truncicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Solanum truncicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were determined as 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum humblotii" order="Solanales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humblotii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Solanum humblotii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; this has caused considerable confusion in herbaria. The two species occur in similar wet forest habitats but are allopatric with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum truncicola" order="Solanales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="truncicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Solanum truncicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having a more southerly distribution and at higher elevations than 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Solanum humblotii" order="Solanales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="humblotii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Solanum humblotii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="104" pageNumber="105">
Although the original spelling of the epithet is &quot; 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">truncicolum</emphasis>
&quot; (
<bibRefCitation author="Bitter, G" journalOrPublisher="Botanische Jahrbuecher fuer Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="416 - 506" refId="B5" refString="Bitter, G, 1917. Solana Africana II. Botanische Jahrbuecher fuer Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie 54: 416 - 506" title="Solana Africana II." volume="54" year="1917">Bitter 1917</bibRefCitation>
) the word element - 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">cola</emphasis>
should be treated as a noun in apposition and this is a correctable error to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Solanaceae" genus="Solanum" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="truncicola" order="Solanales" pageId="104" pageNumber="105" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="truncicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">truncicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Article 23.5, 
<bibRefCitation author="McNeill, J" journalOrPublisher="Koelz Scientific Books, Koenigstein" pageId="110" pageNumber="111" refId="B82" refString="McNeill, J, Barrie, FR, Demoulin, V, Greuter, W, Hawksworth, DL, Herendeen, PS, Knapp, S, Marhold, K, Prado, J, Prud'homme van Reine, WF, Smith, GF, Weirsema, JH, Turland, NJ, 2012. International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code). Regnum Vegetabile 152. Koelz Scientific Books, Koenigstein" title="International Code of Nomenclature for algae, fungi, and plants (Melbourne Code). Regnum Vegetabile 152" year="2012">McNeill et al. 2012</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="104" pageNumber="105">
Label details on 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Malcomber et al. 1353</emphasis>
(MO) record the pedicel and calyx as dark purple. The anthers on at least one flower of 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="104" pageNumber="105">Malcomber et al. 1353</emphasis>
are clearly connate but distinctly free on other flowers of the same specimen and on other collections.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="104" pageNumber="105">
<bibRefCitation author="Bitter, G" journalOrPublisher="Botanische Jahrbuecher fuer Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" pagination="416 - 506" refId="B5" refString="Bitter, G, 1917. Solana Africana II. Botanische Jahrbuecher fuer Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie 54: 416 - 506" title="Solana Africana II." volume="54" year="1917">Bitter (1917)</bibRefCitation>
cited three herbaria in the protologue - G-Boiss., B and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Haussknecht”">&quot;Haussknecht&quot;</normalizedToken>
(now held in JE). We have selected the duplicate at JE as the lectotype because it bears an annotation label in 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Bitter’s">Bitter's</normalizedToken>
handwriting and is a larger specimen with more flowers than that at G.
</paragraph>
